<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection xml:id="binomial-in-R-Instat">
      <title>
        Working with the binomial distribution in R-Instat
      </title>
      
      <p>
        Although some people find it handy to know the formulas in Table <xref ref="table-distribution-formulas"/>, 
        most people just want to know how to use the distributions without worrying too much about the maths. To that end, 
        R has a function called <c>dbinom()</c> that calculates binomial probabilities for us. The main arguments to the function are
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <c>x</c>. This is a number, or vector of numbers, specifying the outcomes whose probability you're trying to calculate.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <c>size</c>. This is a number telling R the size of the experiment.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <c>prob</c>. This is the success probability for any one trial in the experiment.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      
      <p>
        To calculate the probability of obtaining 4 successes from an experiment of 20 trials, where the probability of success on each trial is 1/6, 
        use the Show Model dialog in R-Instat through <em>Model Menu <m>\rightarrow</m> Probality Distributions <m>\rightarrow</m> Show Model...</em> as show in the image below.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="model_menu">
        <caption>Model Menu Navigation</caption>
        <image source="images\intro-to_probability\model_menu.png">
          <shortdescription>Model Menu Naviagtion</shortdescription>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        This will open the dialog below, and you can use the sample dataset shown alongside. You can type into a spreadsheet or notepad and import it in format supported by R_Instat.
      </p>
      <p>
        In the inputs of the dialog;
      </p>
      <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-show_model_steps">
          <title>Steps</title>
          <p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Select the <em>Probabilites</em>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  In <em>Values</em>, enter 4 (or select the variable containing the observed values, e.g. Skulls). 
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Select <em>Binomial</em> as the <em>Distribution</em>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  In <em>mean</em>, enter <m>20</m> to specify the number of trials.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  In <em>Probability</em>, enter <m>\frac{1}{6} (or 0.166667)</m> as the probability of success.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Click <em>OK</em>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
            
            R-Instat generates the output equivalent R command:
            <em><m>dbinom(x = 4, size = 20, prob = 1/6)</m></em>
            which returns:
            <em><m>[1] 0.005909</m></em>
          </p>
        </assemblage>
      <figure xml:id="show_model_dialog">
        <caption>Show Model Dialog with Dataset Used</caption>
        <image source="images\intro-to_probability\show_model_dlg.png">
          <shortdescription>Show Model Dialog</shortdescription>
        </image>
      </figure>
      
      <figure xml:id="show_model_output">
        <caption>Binomial Distribution Output</caption>
        <image source="images\intro-to_probability\show_model_output.png">
          <shortdescription>Binomial Output</shortdescription>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        To give you a feel for how the binomial distribution changes when we alter the values of <m>\theta</m> and <m>N</m>, let's suppose that instead of rolling dice, 
        I'm actually flipping coins. This time around, my experiment involves flipping a fair coin repeatedly, and the outcome that I'm interested in is the number of heads that I observe. 
        In this scenario, the success probability is now <m>\theta = 1/2</m>. Suppose I were to flip the coin <m>N=20</m> times. In this example, 
        I've changed the success probability, but kept the size of the experiment the same. What does this do to our binomial distribution? Well, as <xref ref="fig-binomial2a"/> shows, 
        the main effect of this is to shift the whole distribution, as you'd expect. Okay, what if we flipped a coin <m>N=100</m> times? 
        Well, in that case, we get <xref ref="fig-binomial2b"/>. The distribution stays roughly in the middle, but there's a bit more variability in the possible outcomes.
      </p>
      
      <figure xml:id="fig-binomial2a">
        <caption>The binomial distributions which I'm flipping a fair coin, so the
          underlying success probability is theta = 1/2. We assume I'm 
          flipping the coin N = 20 times.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/binomial2a.png"/>
      </figure>
      
      <figure xml:id="fig-binomial2b">
        <caption>The binomial distributions which I'm flipping a fair coin, so the
          underlying success probability is theta = 1/2. We assume I'm 
          flipping the coin N = 100 times.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/binomial2b.png"/>
      </figure>
      <p>
        So far, we have used the Show Model dialog to calculate probabilities for a selected distribution. 
        Although R-Instat provides a graphical interface, every calculation is performed using the R statistical language in the background. 
        If you select To Script before running the dialog, or view the R Script window, you can see the R command that R-Instat generates automatically.
      </p>
      <p>
        R uses a consistent naming convention for probability distributions. 
        For every distribution, including the Binomial and Normal distributions, 
        there are four related functions. Each function performs a different type of calculation, 
        as shown in <xref ref="table-r-prefix-functions"/>.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-r-prefix-functions">
        <title>R functions for probability distributions</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
            <cell halign="left">what it does</cell>
            <cell>prefix</cell>
            <cell>normal distribution</cell>
            <cell>binomial distribution</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell halign="left">probability (density) of</cell>
            <cell><m>d</m></cell>
            <cell><c>dnorm()</c></cell>
            <cell><c>dbinom()</c></cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell halign="left">cumulative probability of</cell>
            <cell><m>p</m></cell>
            <cell><c>pnorm()</c></cell>
            <cell><c>pbinom()</c></cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell halign="left">generate random number from</cell>
            <cell><m>r</m></cell>
            <cell><c>rnorm()</c></cell>
            <cell><c>rbinom()</c></cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell halign="left">quantile of</cell>
            <cell><m>q</m></cell>
            <cell><c>qnorm()</c></cell>
            <cell><c>qbinom()</c></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>

      <p>
        You do not need to memorise these function names to use R-Instat. 
        The Show Model dialog automatically generates the appropriate R function according to the options you choose. 
        However, understanding these functions is useful when reading the generated R code or when working directly in R.
      </p>
      
      <p>
        Unlike R, where each function is typed separately, 
        R-Instat combines these calculations into a single dialog. 
        The calculation that is performed depends on the selected tab and the information entered.
      </p>
      <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-show-odel-dialog">
        <title>The Show Model Dialog</title>
        <p>
          The <term>Show Model Dialog</term> contains two tabs:
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                Quantiles
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Probabilities
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </assemblage>
      <sidebyside>
        <figure xml:id="show_quantiles">
          <caption>Show Models Dialog; Quantiles Tab</caption>
          <image source="images\intro-to_probability\show_quantiles.png">
            <shortdescription>The show dialog showing inputs in the Quantiles Tab</shortdescription>
          </image>
        </figure>
        <figure xml:id="show_probabilities">
          <caption>Show Models Dialog; Probabilities Tab</caption>
          <image source="images\intro-to_probability\show_probabilities.png">
            <shortdescription>The show dialog showing inputs in the Probabilities Tab</shortdescription>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </sidebyside>
      <p>
        Both tabs share several common controls. 
        First, select the Data Frame that contains your data. Next, 
        choose the required probability model from the Distribution drop-down list. 
        Throughout this chapter we continue using the Binomial distribution, 
        although many other probability distributions are available.
      </p>
      <p>
        Once a distribution has been selected, the Distribution Parameters section changes automatically to display the parameters required for that distribution. For example, 
        the Normal distribution requires a Mean and Standard Deviation, 
        whereas the Binomial distribution requires the Number of trials and the Probability of success.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <term>Graph</term> and <term>Values</term> options determine how the results are displayed. 
        Selecting <em>Graph</em> displays the graphical output, 
        while <em>Values</em> displays the corresponding numerical output.
      </p>
      <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-quantile-tab">
        <title>The Quantile Tab</title>
        <p>
          The Quantiles tab is used when the value of the random variable is known and you want to determine its probability.
        </p>
        <p>
          The <term>Values</term> input box is used to enter one or more observed values. 
          For a Binomial distribution, these values represent the number of successes. 
          Together with the selected distribution parameters, 
          R-Instat calculates the corresponding probability.
        </p>
        <p>
          The Quantiles tab is used when the value of the random variable is known and you want to determine its probability.
        </p>
        <p>
          Although this tab is labelled <em>Quantiles</em>, it allows you to enter one or more values and determine the associated probabilities for the selected distribution.
        </p>
      </assemblage>
      <p>
        For example, suppose a die is rolled <m>20</m> times and the probability of rolling a skull is <m>\frac{1}{6}</m>. 
        Enter:
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Values: 4
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Distribution: Binomial
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Number of Trials: 20
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Probability: <m>\frac{1}{6}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
        R-Instat calculates the required probability for the entered value using the selected distribution. 
        The generated R code can be viewed from the <term>To Script</term> button before running the dialog.
      </p>
      <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-probabilities-tab">
        <title>The Probabilities Tab</title>
        <p>
          The <term>Probabilities</term> tab performs the reverse calculation. 
          Instead of entering an observed value, 
          you enter one or more probability values between 0 and 1.
        </p>
        <p>
          The <term>Probabilities</term> input box accepts one or more probability values between 0 and 1, 
          and R-Instat calculates the corresponding quantile (cut-off value) for the selected distribution. 
          For example, entering <m>0.50</m> returns the median of the selected distribution, 
          while entering <m>0.95</m> returns the value below which <m>95%</m> of the observations are expected to occur.
        </p>
        <p>
          As with the Quantiles tab, the Distribution and Distribution Parameters determine the probability model being used, 
          while the Graph and Values options control whether the results are displayed graphically or numerically.
        </p>
        <p>
          The two tabs therefore complement each other. The Quantiles tab starts with a value and finds its probability, 
          whereas the Probabilities tab starts with a probability and finds the corresponding value. 
          R-Instat automatically generates the appropriate R command for each calculation, 
          allowing you to perform the analysis through the graphical interface while still learning the equivalent R code.
        </p>
      </assemblage>
      <p>
        The <em>Show Model</em> dialog brings together several related calculations that would normally require different R functions. 
        Rather than remembering whether to use <c>dbinom(), pbinom(), qbinom()</c> or another function, 
        the user simply selects the appropriate tab and enters the required information. 
        R-Instat then generates the correct R command automatically.
      </p>
    </subsection>